    <article class="recipe">
        <h1>Sweet Potato and Black Bean Burritos</h1>

        
        
        <span class="published"><span class="value-title" title="2011-07-31"></span></span>
        
        
                            
      
        
        <h3 class="recipe_source">
            
                <a href="http://www.womansday.com/" target="_blank">Woman's Day</a>
            
        </h3>
                            



        


        
        <figure class="recipeimg">
        <img src="/cm/womansday/images/IB/Sweet-Potato-and-Black-Bean-Burritos-Recipe-lg.jpg" />
            <figcaption>Antonis Achilleos/Woman's Day</figcaption>
        </figure>
        

        <h2 class="deck"><span class="summary">You won't even miss the meat when it's substituted with saut&#233;ed sweet potatoes. It's filling, fiber-rich and plays well with creamy black beans. Also, crisping the outside of each burrito may seem unnecessary, but it&#146;s definitely well worth the effort.</span></h2>
        <p class="byline">By <span class="author">Woman's Day Kitchen </span></p>
    
        <section class="yield">
              
            <p class="duration">
                
                30 min
                <!--<span class="value-title" title="PT
                30M"></span> -->                       
            </p>
            <p class="preptime">
                
                30 min
                <!--<span class="value-title" title="PT
                30M"></span> -->                       
            </p>
            
            
        </section>


        <section class="recipeingredients">
                
                
                
                <p class="ingredient">
                    2
                    tablespoon(s)
                    
                    olive oil 
                </p>
                
                <p class="ingredient">
                    1
                    large
                    
                    sweet potato, peeled and cut into 1/2-in. pieces
                </p>
                
                <p class="ingredient">
                    1
                    medium
                    
                    red onion, half chopped and half thinly sliced
                </p>
                
                <p class="ingredient">
                    
                    
                    
                    Kosher salt and pepper 
                </p>
                
                <p class="ingredient">
                    1 15.5-
                    ounce(s)
                    
                    can black beans, rinsed
                </p>
                
                <p class="ingredient">
                    1
                    tablespoon(s)
                    
                    chopped chipotle peppers in adobo
                </p>
                
                <p class="ingredient">
                    1
                    small
                    
                    bunch spinach, thick stems discarded, leaves coarsely chopped
                </p>
                
                <p class="ingredient">
                    6-
                    ounce(s)
                    
                    Monterey Jack cheese, coarsely grated
                </p>
                
                <p class="ingredient">
                    4
                    large
                    
                    flour tortillas
                </p>
                
                <p class="ingredient">
                    2
                    tablespoon(s)
                    
                    lowfat sour cream
                </p>
                
                <p class="ingredient">
                    2
                    tablespoon(s)
                    
                    fresh lime juice, plus wedges for serving
                </p>
                
                <p class="ingredient">
                    0.5
                    head(s)
                    
                    romaine lettuce, sliced into 1/2-in.-thick strips
                </p>
                
                
        </section>



        
        <ul class="nutritional_info">
            <lh>Nutritional Information <span>(per serving)</span></lh>
            <li class="calories">
                <strong>544</strong>
            </li>
            <li class="total_fat">
                25g
            </li>
            <li class="saturated_fat">
                10g
            </li>
            <li class="cholesterol">
                39mg
            </li>
            <li class="sodium">
                1213mg
            </li>
            <li class="total_carbohydrates">
                58g
            </li>
            <li class="fiber">
                12g
            </li>
            <li class="sugar">
                n/a
            </li>
            <li class="protein">
                24g
            </li>
            <li class="calcium">
                --
            </li>
        </ul>

        
        <section class="directions">
                <ol class="directions instructions">
                
                    
                    <li><span>Heat 1 Tbsp of the oil in a large skillet over medium heat. Add the sweet potato, chopped onion and 1/2 tsp salt and cook, covered, stirring occasionally, until tender, 10 to 12 minutes.</span></li>
                    <li><span>Add the beans and chipotles and cook, stirring occasionally, for 2 minutes. Add the spinach and cook, tossing, until it begins to wilt, 1 to 2 minutes. Divide the cheese and potato-bean mixture among the tortillas (about 1 cup each) and roll up to form burritos. Wipe out the skillet and heat over medium heat. Cook the burritos (seam-side down first) until golden brown, 2 to 3 minutes per side.</span></li>
                    <li><span>Meanwhile, in a medium bowl, whisk together the sour cream, lime juice, remaining Tbsp oil, and 1/4 each tsp salt and pepper. Add the romaine and sliced onions and toss to coat. Serve with the burritos and lime wedges, if desired.</span></li>                     
                
                </ol>
                
                <hr />
                
                <p class="header">Tips & Techniques</p>
                <div class="tips_wrapper">
                    <p class="tips">Chop the leftover chipotles and divide the pieces and remaining adobo sauce among the sections of an ice cube tray. Freeze, then transfer cubes to a freezer-safe container. Toss into chili or stew.</p>
                </div>
                
                <!--concordance-end-->
                
                
                   
        </section>
    </article>


            
			
			
            
            
            
            

            
            
            
            
            
            
            
            
            
            

			
            
            
        
			


